Function for Confusion Matrix¶

In [219]:
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted, [1,0] )
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = ["Default", "No Default"] , yticklabels = ["Default", "No Default"] )
   # plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    sns.set(font_scale=0.4)
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.show()

def r_squared(model, X, y):
    y_mean = y_train.mean()
    SST = ((y_train - y_mean)**2).sum()
    SSE = ((y_train - regression_model.predict(X_train))**2).sum()
    r_square = 1 - SSE/SST
    return SSE, SST, r_square

With the coefficient values we can interpret that

Values with positive coefficient - when value of the independent variable increases, the probability of person taking loan will increase
Values with negative coefficient - when value of the independent variable increases, the probability of person taking loan will decrease

WIth P values

Except ID , all attributes have values less than 0.05 and many has values as 0.00 - SO enough evidence to reject null hypothesis and there is non - zero correlation

All SE are less values - a good thing !
